def max_groups(grades):
    grades.sort()

    dp = [1] * len(grades)

    for i in range(len(grades)):
        for j in range(i):
            if grades[i] + dp[j] * grades[j] > (i+1) * grades[j]:
                dp[i] = dp[j] + 1

    return dp[-1]
```


    First, we sort the `grades` array in ascending order. Then, we create an array `dp` of the same length initialized with all ones because the minimum number of groups for any element is 1.

We iterate through the `grades` in two nested loops where the inner loop iterates up to the current index of the outer loop. Using dynamic programming, we check if `(grades[i] + dp[j] * grades[j])` is greater than `((i+1) * grades[j])`. If it is, we update `dp[i] = dp[j] + 1`. When the last element of `dp` is reached, this will contain the maximum number of groups possible.

